---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<!doctype html>

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />

    <meta
      name="viewport"
      content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"
    />

    <title>
      The Theory of Minimal Tolerance
    </title>

    <meta
      name="description"
      content="The moral and economic foundations of the Theory of Minimal Tolerance."
    />

    <link
      rel="canonical"
      href="https://minimaltolerance.com/theory"
    />
  </head>

  <body>
    <Header />

    <main>

      <!-- PAGE INTRO -->

      <section class="page-hero">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THEORY
          </p>

          <h1>
            Minimal Tolerance
          </h1>

          <p class="lead">
            Coercion is never legitimate.
            At most, its limited use may be tolerated.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- MORAL PROBLEM -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE MORAL PROBLEM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Political authority rests on coercion
          </h2>

          <p>
            Taxation is not voluntary. Compliance ultimately rests
            on the threat of sanction. Elections, constitutions and
            legal procedures may regulate coercion, but they do not
            transform it into consent.
          </p>

          <p>
            The relationship between the individual and the State
            is neither contractual nor optional. Political authority
            is imposed territorially, and the individual remains
            subject to it regardless of personal agreement.
          </p>

          <p>
            The capacity to enforce a rule does not create a moral
            right to impose it. Power and legitimacy are different
            things.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- EFFICIENCY PROBLEM -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE EFFICIENCY PROBLEM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Coercion does not solve the knowledge problem
          </h2>

          <p>
            The knowledge required to coordinate a complex society
            is dispersed among millions of individuals. It is local,
            contextual and constantly changing.
          </p>

          <p>
            Market prices communicate information about scarcity,
            preferences and opportunity costs. Political institutions
            cannot reproduce that process through centralized
            decision-making.
          </p>

          <p>
            The State replaces decentralized choices with political
            direction while operating with less information, weaker
            feedback and fewer mechanisms for correcting error.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- CENTRAL STATEMENT -->

      <section class="statement">

        <blockquote>
          A coercive relationship does not become voluntary
          because coercion is regulated.
        </blockquote>

      </section>

      <!-- LEGITIMACY AND TOLERANCE -->

      <section class="content-section">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            LEGITIMACY AND TOLERANCE
          </p>

          <h2>
            Necessity does not create legitimacy
          </h2>

          <p>
            A practical problem does not create a moral right to
            coerce. Even where voluntary coordination faces a real
            limit, coercion remains coercion.
          </p>

          <p>
            Minimal Tolerance separates moral legitimacy from
            practical tolerance. The State never becomes legitimate.
            Its limited use may only be tolerated as an exceptional
            response to a demonstrated necessity.
          </p>

          <p>
            Tolerance is not approval. It defines the narrow boundary
            between what must be rejected and what may be reluctantly
            accepted.
          </p>

        </div>

      </section>

      <!-- NEXT PAGE -->

      <section class="content-section content-section-alt">

        <div class="container">

          <p class="eyebrow">
            THE THEOREM
          </p>

          <h2>
            Defining the exception
          </h2>

          <p>
            The Minimal Tolerance Theorem establishes the conditions
            required before any use of state coercion may be
            tolerated.
          </p>

          <div class="buttons">

            <a href="/theorem" class="primary">
              Read the Theorem
            </a>

          </div>

        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
